name: Stanley Chapple
comments: Born in London, he studied at the London Academy of Music where he was successively student, professor, Vice-principle and until 1936 principle. In 1920, at the age of nineteen, he was hired as director of the City of London School's opera, but more importantly for us he was also hired by the Aeolian Vocalion Company as and piano accompanist. By 1924 he became music director, a position he held about 1929. Chapple's plan to tour the Soviet Union was thwarted by the outbreak of World War II in 1939. He was in the USA at the time and conducted the National Symphony Orchestra at the Watergate Barge Concerts. In 1940 he became director of the school for conducting and orchestral music founded by the Boston Symphony Orchestra, which became Tanglewood. One of his first students there was Leonard Bernstein. He became an American citizen and in 1950 became conductor of the Seattle Symphony, and later a.o. the Seattle Senior Symphony.

name: Jim Connell
comments: Political activist of the late 19th century and early 20th century, best known as the writer of the anthem "The Red Flag" in December 1889. He was born in Kilskyre, Ireland. As a teenager, he became involved in land agitation and joined the Irish Republican Brotherhood. At 18 he moved to Dublin, where he worked as a casual docker, but was blacklisted for his attempts to unionise the docks. Failing to find any other work, he left for London in 1875, where he spent most of the rest of his life. He worked at a variety of jobs. He was a staff journalist on Kier Hardie’s newspaper “The Labour Leader” and was secretary of the Workingmen’s Legal Aid Society during the last 20 years of his life.
